Britain gave the IEBC Sh1.5 billion for strengthening operations as voter registration kicked off countrywide on Monday.High Commissioner Nic Hailey said they were impressed by the manner in which the exercise has been handled in various parts so far."It is very exciting to witness Kenyan democracy in action," he said on Monday.Hailey visited IEBC offices in Eldoret, Uasin Gishu county, and other parts of the Rift Valley to asses voter registration and general preparedness.He also held separate meetings with Catholic Bishop Cornelius Korir, Governor Jackson Mandago and county commissioner Abdi Hassan.Read: Low turnout in Siaya as drought forces Samburus to stay away from polling centresAlso read: Low turnout, apathy mark day 1 of voter listing in hot spot MombasaThe High Commissioner said Britain wants to ensure the August 8 poll is credible, free and fair."We are not playing politics but are helping build the capacity of the IEBC as it prepares for the elections," he said.Noting the support followed a request by the Kenyan government, he said his country will also support civic education programmes.Read: US to support Kenya's 2017 election process, says no hidden agendaThe envoy visited MV Patel Hall in Eldoret where registration was taking place. He will later head to Kakamega and Kisumu counties for the same exercise.Hundreds of people turned up to register at centres in parts of Eldoret but some hitches were reported.&ldquo;We have a few hiccups especially for those who want to change their polling stations because they are being told to wait&rdquo;, said Huruma MCA Peter Chomba.But Chomba and Rift Council of Imams and Preachers chair Abubakar Bini, asked more Kenyans to turn up.&ldquo;As Kenyans we are used to complaining when things go wrong. This is the time to register so that we have an opportunity to elect the leaders we want&rdquo;, Bini said.The county commissioner said security had been tightened in all areas and that they were working with the IEBC for a smooth process.Supporters of the ruling Jubilee Party and opposition group NASA have started mobilising residents for the month-long exercise.Cornelius Saina, Amani coalition North Rift official, said they were sensitising the public on the importance of registering as voters.&ldquo;Our aim is to ensure safety for all Kenyans so that no one misses to register," he said.Read: NASA frustrating Jubilee plot to rig August election, Orengo saysAlso read: Be patient with IEBC, Raila tells Kenyans as voter registration begins